---

<BaseLayout title="Citizenship — 2-Year Path Guide | Argentina's Golden Visa">
  <Header />
  <main>
    <PageHero 
      title="Argentina Golden Visa"
      subtitle="Your Path to Residency & Citizenship"
      description="The Argentina Golden Visa is the two-year path from residency to citizenship: temporary residency, then permanent residency, then citizenship—with a strong passport and Mercosur access."
      image="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1589909202802-8f4aadce1849?w=1920&q=80"
      breadcrumbs={[{ label: 'Argentina Golden Visa', href: '/citizenship' }]}
    />

    <!-- Overview Section -->
    <section class="section-padding bg-white">
      <div class="container-luxury">
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-16 items-center">
          <div>
            <p class="label-small mb-4">Why Argentine Citizenship?</p>
            <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light text-charcoal mb-6">
              The Argentina Golden Visa: A Two-Year Path to Citizenship
            </h2>
            <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-6">
              The <strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">Argentina Golden Visa</strong> is the common name for Argentina’s path from legal residency to citizenship. Unlike many countries that require five to ten years of residence, Argentina allows you to apply for citizenship after two years of legal residency. There is no separate “golden visa” law; the term refers to this fast track: obtain temporary residency (through investment, retirement, or passive income), convert to permanent residency when eligible, and after two years of residency apply for citizenship. The outcome is one of the most valuable passports in the Americas, dual citizenship allowed, and access to Mercosur and visa-free travel to 170+ countries.
            </p>
            <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-6">
              Argentine citizenship gives you full rights to live, work, and own property in Argentina, plus visa-free or visa-on-arrival access to the European Union, the United Kingdom, and most of Latin America. Argentina permits dual citizenship, so you keep your existing nationality. Below we outline the exact pathway from temporary to permanent residency to citizenship, the timeline and milestones, document requirements at each stage, dual citizenship rules, benefits (including passport strength and Mercosur), and common pitfalls to avoid.
            </p>
            <div class="flex gap-8">
              <div>
                <p class="font-serif text-4xl text-charcoal mb-1">2</p>
                <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-light">Years to Citizenship</p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <p class="font-serif text-4xl text-charcoal mb-1">170+</p>
                <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-light">Visa-Free Countries</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="relative h-[500px]">
            <img
              src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1612294037637-ec328d0e075e?w=800&q=80"
              alt="Argentine citizenship and passport, Argentina Golden Visa path"
              class="w-full h-full object-cover"
              style="filter: saturate(0.9);"
              width="800"
              height="500"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Pathway: Temporary → Permanent → Citizenship -->
    <section class="section-padding bg-cream-light">
      <div class="container-luxury max-w-3xl">
        <p class="label-small mb-4">The Pathway</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light text-charcoal mb-8">
          From Temporary Residency to Citizenship
        </h2>
        <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-10">
          The Argentina Golden Visa path has three clear stages. Understanding each stage helps you plan and avoid gaps that can delay or jeopardize your citizenship application.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-light text-charcoal mb-4">Stage 1: Temporary Residency</h3>
        <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-6">
          You first obtain temporary residency (residencia temporal) through one of the routes recognized by Migraciones: investor (Inversionista), retiree (Pensionado), rentista (passive income), or other categories such as family reunification or employment. You apply at an Argentine consulate abroad or at the Dirección Nacional de Migraciones if you are already in Argentina. Approval typically takes a few months. You receive a temporary DNI (Documento Nacional de Identidad) and must comply with the conditions of your visa (e.g. maintaining the investment or proving pension income). Temporary residency is usually granted for one to three years and can be renewed. This period counts toward the two years required for citizenship eligibility only once you have upgraded to permanent residency; some interpretations allow counting from the start of temporary residency—confirm with Migraciones or your lawyer.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-light text-charcoal mb-4">Stage 2: Permanent Residency</h3>
        <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-6">
          After holding temporary residency for the required period (often three years for investor and similar categories, though rules can vary), you apply for permanent residency (residencia permanente). You submit updated documentation proving you have met the conditions of your temporary visa and have not breached immigration or criminal rules. Once permanent residency is granted, you receive a permanent DNI. There is no annual cap on permanent residency; the main requirement is having fulfilled the temporary-residency period and continuing to meet the criteria Migraciones applies at the time of your application. Permanent residency does not expire and allows you to live, work, and study in Argentina without renewing a visa.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-2xl font-light text-charcoal mb-4">Stage 3: Citizenship</h3>
        <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed">
          After two years of legal residency (interpreted by most courts as two years from the date permanent residency was granted, though some count from the start of temporary residency), you may apply for Argentine citizenship. The application is filed with the federal court (juzgado federal) in your jurisdiction. You must demonstrate continuous residence, basic Spanish, knowledge of Argentine history and the Constitution, and good conduct. The court may request an interview and will verify your documents. Processing can take from several months to over a year depending on the court. Upon approval, you take the oath of allegiance and receive your Argentine citizenship and passport. This is the final step of the Argentina Golden Visa path.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Timeline and Milestones -->
    <section class="section-padding bg-white">
      <div class="container-luxury">
        <p class="label-small mb-4">Timeline</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light text-charcoal mb-8">
          Milestones from Residency to Citizenship
        </h2>
        <div class="max-w-3xl">
          <div class="space-y-6 mb-10">
            <div class="flex gap-6 items-start border-l-2 border-bronze pl-6">
              <span class="font-sans text-sm font-medium text-bronze whitespace-nowrap">Month 0</span>
              <div>
                <p class="font-serif text-lg text-charcoal mb-1">Apply for temporary residency</p>
                <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm">Submit application (consulate or Migraciones). Gather passports, criminal clearances, proof of funds or pension, and any investment documentation.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-6 items-start border-l-2 border-gray-border pl-6">
              <span class="font-sans text-sm font-medium text-gray-light whitespace-nowrap">Months 2–4</span>
              <div>
                <p class="font-serif text-lg text-charcoal mb-1">Temporary residency granted</p>
                <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm">Receive temporary DNI. Comply with visa conditions and maintain residence as required.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-6 items-start border-l-2 border-gray-border pl-6">
              <span class="font-sans text-sm font-medium text-gray-light whitespace-nowrap">Year 3 (typical)</span>
              <div>
                <p class="font-serif text-lg text-charcoal mb-1">Apply for permanent residency</p>
                <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm">After the required period of temporary residency, apply to upgrade. Processing may take several months.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-6 items-start border-l-2 border-gray-border pl-6">
              <span class="font-sans text-sm font-medium text-gray-light whitespace-nowrap">Permanent DNI issued</span>
              <div>
                <p class="font-serif text-lg text-charcoal mb-1">Start of two-year count for citizenship</p>
                <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm">The two years of residency required for citizenship are typically counted from this date.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-6 items-start border-l-2 border-gray-border pl-6">
              <span class="font-sans text-sm font-medium text-gray-light whitespace-nowrap">Year 5 (typical)</span>
              <div>
                <p class="font-serif text-lg text-charcoal mb-1">Apply for citizenship</p>
                <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm">File with the federal court. Provide proof of residence, DNI, criminal clearances, and evidence of Spanish and civic knowledge.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex gap-6 items-start border-l-2 border-bronze pl-6">
              <span class="font-sans text-sm font-medium text-bronze whitespace-nowrap">Months 6–18 later</span>
              <div>
                <p class="font-serif text-lg text-charcoal mb-1">Citizenship granted</p>
                <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm">Court approval, oath, and issuance of Argentine citizenship and passport. Total timeline from first application: approximately 5.5–7 years (2–3 years temporary + permanent upgrade + 2 years residence + processing).</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm italic">
            Note: If your country has a special agreement with Argentina or you qualify under a different provision, the residency period may be shorter. Always confirm current rules with Migraciones or your legal advisor.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Dual Citizenship -->
    <section class="section-padding bg-cream-light">
      <div class="container-luxury max-w-3xl">
        <p class="label-small mb-4">Dual Nationality</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light text-charcoal mb-6">
          Dual Citizenship Rules
        </h2>
        <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Argentina allows dual (and multiple) citizenship. You do not have to renounce your existing nationality when you become Argentine. The Argentine state does not require you to choose one passport over another for most purposes. You can hold an Argentine passport alongside your other passports and use each according to the rules of the country you are entering or leaving.
        </p>
        <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Your country of origin may have its own rules: some countries restrict or discourage dual citizenship, or require you to inform authorities. It is your responsibility to check whether your home country recognizes dual citizenship and whether you need to declare your Argentine citizenship. Argentina’s position is clear: acquiring Argentine citizenship does not require you to give up another nationality, and losing or renouncing another nationality is not a condition of keeping Argentine citizenship once granted.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Process Steps -->
    <section class="section-padding bg-cream-light">
      <div class="container-luxury">
        <div class="text-center mb-16">
          <p class="label-small mb-4">The Process</p>
          <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light text-charcoal mb-4">
            Your Path to Citizenship
          </h2>
          <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed max-w-2xl mx-auto">
            Six steps from first residency to citizenship. For the full pathway (temporary → permanent → citizenship), timeline, and document lists, see the sections above.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
          {steps.map((step) => (
            <div class="bg-white p-8 border border-gray-border">
              <p class="font-serif text-4xl text-bronze/30 mb-4">{step.number}</p>
              <h3 class="font-serif text-xl text-charcoal mb-3">{step.title}</h3>
              <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed">
                {step.description}
              </p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Benefits -->
    <section class="section-padding bg-white">
      <div class="container-luxury">
        <div class="text-center mb-12">
          <p class="label-small mb-4">Benefits</p>
          <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light text-charcoal mb-6">
            Why Become an Argentine Citizen
          </h2>
          <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed max-w-2xl mx-auto mb-4">
            Argentine citizenship delivers a strong passport, regional mobility through Mercosur, and full rights in Argentina. Below are the main benefits of completing the Argentina Golden Visa path.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto mb-12">
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-light text-charcoal mb-4">Passport strength</h3>
          <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The Argentine passport offers visa-free or visa-on-arrival access to more than 170 countries and territories. That includes the entire Schengen Area (European Union plus associated states), the United Kingdom, and most of Latin America. For many investors and families, this level of access—obtainable after two years of residency—compares favorably to longer naturalization periods elsewhere. Passport rankings vary by index, but Argentina consistently ranks among the most powerful passports in the Americas.
          </p>
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-light text-charcoal mb-4">Mercosur access</h3>
          <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed">
            As an Argentine citizen you are part of Mercosur (Mercado Común del Sur). Mercosur membership allows you to live, work, and study in other member states (Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay, and associated countries) under simplified rules. That gives you and your family mobility across a large part of South America without needing separate work or residence permits in each country. For business or lifestyle reasons, Mercosur access is a concrete advantage of the Argentina Golden Visa outcome.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
          {benefits.map((benefit) => (
            <div class="text-center p-8">
              <h3 class="font-serif text-xl text-charcoal mb-3">{benefit.title}</h3>
              <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed">
                {benefit.description}
              </p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Document Requirements at Each Stage -->
    <section class="section-padding bg-cream-light">
      <div class="container-luxury max-w-3xl">
        <p class="label-small mb-4">Documents</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light text-charcoal mb-8">
          Document Requirements at Each Stage
        </h2>
        <p class="font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed mb-10">
          Requirements vary by visa category and by office. The lists below are a guide; always confirm with Migraciones, the consulate, or your lawyer before applying.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-light text-charcoal mb-4">Temporary residency (first application)</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 mb-8 font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed">
          <li>Valid passport (full copy, minimum validity as required)</li>
          <li>Birth certificate (apostilled or legalized)</li>
          <li>Criminal record certificate from country of residence and, if applicable, from Argentina (apostilled/legalized)</li>
          <li>Proof of funds, pension, or investment depending on visa type (bank statements, tax returns, investment contracts, etc.)</li>
          <li>Proof of address in Argentina if applying in-country</li>
          <li>Payment of migration fees (UMSM-based)</li>
          <li>Any category-specific documents (e.g. investment plan for investor visa, pension letter for Pensionado)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-light text-charcoal mb-4">Permanent residency (upgrade)</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 mb-8 font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed">
          <li>Current temporary DNI and passport</li>
          <li>Proof you have met the conditions of your temporary residency for the required period (e.g. continued investment, pension income)</li>
          <li>Updated criminal clearances if requested</li>
          <li>Proof of address and, where relevant, proof of means of support</li>
          <li>Payment of applicable fees</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-xl font-light text-charcoal mb-4">Citizenship application (federal court)</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed">
          <li>Permanent DNI and passport</li>
          <li>Proof of two years of legal residence (utility bills, rental contracts, tax filings, or other evidence the court accepts)</li>
          <li>Criminal record certificate from Argentina and from country of origin or last residence (recent, apostilled/legalized)</li>
          <li>Proof of means of support (employment, business, pension, or other)</li>
          <li>Evidence of basic Spanish (interview or certificate as required by the court)</li>
          <li>Proof of knowledge of Argentine history and Constitution (as required by the court)</li>
          <li>Birth certificate and any marriage or divorce certificates if relevant</li>
          <li>Court filing fees and any other costs the court specifies</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Common Pitfalls -->
    <section class="section-padding bg-white">
      <div class="container-luxury max-w-3xl">
        <p class="label-small mb-4">What to Avoid</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light text-charcoal mb-8">
          Common Pitfalls on the Argentina Golden Visa Path
        </h2>
        <ul class="space-y-6 font-sans text-base font-light text-gray-warm leading-relaxed">
          <li class="flex gap-4">
            <span class="text-bronze font-serif">1.</span>
            <span><strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">Long absences.</strong> Courts may treat excessive time outside Argentina as a break in residence. If you plan to travel frequently, keep proof of your ties to Argentina (address, taxes, family, business) and avoid absences that exceed what the court or Migraciones considers acceptable for “continuous” residence.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-4">
            <span class="text-bronze font-serif">2.</span>
            <span><strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">Letting temporary residency lapse.</strong> Renew your temporary residency on time. A gap can reset your timeline or complicate your permanent residency application.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-4">
            <span class="text-bronze font-serif">3.</span>
            <span><strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">Applying for citizenship too early.</strong> The two-year period is usually counted from permanent residency. Applying before you have clearly completed two years can lead to rejection or delay.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-4">
            <span class="text-bronze font-serif">4.</span>
            <span><strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">Incomplete or expired documents.</strong> Use recent criminal clearances and apostilled/legalized documents. Expired or improperly legalized papers are a common reason for delays or refusals.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-4">
            <span class="text-bronze font-serif">5.</span>
            <span><strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">Underestimating Spanish and civic knowledge.</strong> Courts expect basic Spanish and some knowledge of Argentine history and the Constitution. Prepare for the interview; failure to demonstrate this can result in denial.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-4">
            <span class="text-bronze font-serif">6.</span>
            <span><strong class="font-normal text-charcoal">Ignoring tax or legal obligations.</strong> Unpaid taxes or run-ins with the law can affect your good-conduct requirement. Stay compliant throughout the residency and citizenship process.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Requirements -->
    <section class="section-padding bg-cream-light">
      <div class="container-luxury">
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-16">
          <div>
            <p class="font-sans text-[11px] font-normal tracking-luxury uppercase text-gray-light mb-4">Requirements</p>
            <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light text-charcoal mb-4">
              What You'll Need
            </h2>
            <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm mb-8">
              Summary of key conditions for the Argentina Golden Visa path. Full document lists at each stage are in the Document Requirements section above.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-4">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-bronze mt-1 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="1.5">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
                </svg>
                <span class="font-sans text-base font-light text-charcoal">Minimum 2 years of legal residency in Argentina</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-bronze mt-1 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="1.5">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
                </svg>
                <span class="font-sans text-base font-light text-charcoal">Valid DNI (national identity document)</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-bronze mt-1 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="1.5">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
                </svg>
                <span class="font-sans text-base font-light text-charcoal">Proof of means of support (employment, business, etc.)</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-bronze mt-1 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="1.5">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
                </svg>
                <span class="font-sans text-base font-light text-charcoal">Clean criminal record (both countries)</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-bronze mt-1 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="1.5">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
                </svg>
                <span class="font-sans text-base font-light text-charcoal">Basic Spanish language proficiency</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-bronze mt-1 flex-shrink-0" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="1.5">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M5 13l4 4L19 7" />
                </svg>
                <span class="font-sans text-base font-light text-charcoal">Knowledge of Argentine history and constitution</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="font-sans text-[11px] font-normal tracking-luxury uppercase text-gray-light mb-4">Timeline</p>
            <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl font-light text-charcoal mb-8">
              Expected Duration
            </h2>
            <div class="space-y-6">
              <div class="border-l-2 border-bronze pl-6">
                <p class="font-serif text-xl text-charcoal mb-1">Residency for citizenship</p>
                <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm">2 years (from permanent residency)</p>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l-2 border-gray-border pl-6">
                <p class="font-serif text-xl text-charcoal mb-1">Citizenship processing</p>
                <p class="font-sans text-sm font-light text-gray-warm">6–18 months</p>
              </div>
